# Function Documentation Standards

## Argument Documentation (`@param`)

Format: `@param par_name par_type. Description of the parameter. Default value is parameter_default.`

- `par_name` MUST exactly match the parameter name in the function signature.
- `par_type` and the description MUST start with a capital letter.
- Include `Default value is <value>.` only when a default is set in the function definition.

```r
# BAD
#' @param data a data frame with pk data
#' @param ci numeric, confidence interval level, default `0.95`

# GOOD
#' @param data Data.frame. A data frame with PK data.
#' @param ci Numeric. Confidence interval level. Default value is `0.95`.
```

## Centralized Argument Documentation

- All reusable `@param` entries MUST be defined in `sg_dummy` in `R/utils.R`.
- Inherit them with `@inheritParams sg_dummy` in every function that shares those arguments.
- If a parameter exists in `sg_dummy` but has a different default or meaning in a specific function, redefine it explicitly in that function's documentation block (overrides the inherited version).

## Special Characters

- Do NOT escape special characters. Write `%` not `\%`, write `>` not `\>`, etc.
- Mark inline code with backticks (`` ` `` ), not `\code{}`.
- Use full `TRUE` and `FALSE`, not `T` or `F`

```r
# BAD
#' Accepts values between 0\% and 100\%.
#' Uses \code{data.frame} internally.
#' Default is `F`

# GOOD
#' Accepts values between 0% and 100%.
#' Uses `data.frame` internally.
#' Default is `FALSE`
```

## Examples (`@examples`)

- Every exported function MUST include at least one `@examples` block.
- Examples MUST be self-contained and executable:
  - Load all required libraries with `library()`.
  - Define or use package-provided objects; do not rely on external files or environment state.

```r
#  BAD
#' @examples
#' fit_model(my_data)

#  GOOD
#' @examples
#' library(simurg)
#' result <- fit_model(example_data)
#' print(result)
```
